The paper deals with the mathematical and computational complexity of minimizing the efficiency gap measure, which is a measure of partisan gerrymandering. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-categories of computer science that deal with algorithms, data structures, computational geometry, game theory, and social and information networks. Specifically, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) are the most likely sub-categories, as the paper provides theoretical and algorithmic analyses of the efficiency gap measure. The sub-categories of cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) are also likely, as the paper deals with the problem of district mapping. Finally, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is a possible sub-category, as the paper deals with the issue of voter disenfranchisement.
